**Idea — Kahn's with min-heap**: At each step pick the smallest-id course with indegree 0. With a simple repeated linear scan (n ≤ 2000) this is O(V^2) and trivial to write.

```javascript
function courseScheduleOrder(numCourses, prerequisites) {
  const adj = Array.from({length: numCourses}, () => []);
  const indeg = new Array(numCourses).fill(0);
  for (const [a, b] of prerequisites) { adj[b].push(a); indeg[a]++; }
  const order = [];
  const taken = new Array(numCourses).fill(false);
  for (let step = 0; step < numCourses; step++) {
    let pick = -1;
    for (let i = 0; i < numCourses; i++) if (!taken[i] && indeg[i] === 0) { pick = i; break; }
    if (pick === -1) return [];
    taken[pick] = true;
    order.push(pick);
    for (const v of adj[pick]) indeg[v]--;
  }
  return order;
}
```

**Time**: O(V^2 + E). **Space**: O(V+E). Heap version: O((V+E) log V).

